			<h1>How to Build a Gingerbread House</h1>
			<h3 id="excerpt"><p>Weekend Holiday Fun </p>
</h3>
			<div class="single_thumbnail">
				<img width="540" height="355" src="http://lovefood.sobeys.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/gingerbread-house-540x355.jpg" class="attachment-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="How to build a gingerbread house" title="gingerbread-house" />	
			</div>
			<div class="entry">
				<p>Decorating a gingerbread house is a holiday activity that has its roots in old European Christmas traditions. Everyone from tiny tots to the young at heart will want to share in the fun, and it couldn’t be simpler to get started.<span id="more-3594"></span></p>
<p>Pick up our no-bake <em>Compliments</em> <strong>Gingerbread House Kit</strong> and you’ll be ready with the perfect diversion for a snowy afternoon. Not to mention you’ll keep the kids entertained for at least a few hours. The easy-to-assemble kit includes snowmen, trees and five kinds of candy&#8211;everything you&#8217;ll need to create the ultimate gingerbread house.</p>
<p>Share the fun, and host a holiday cookie decorating party. Our <strong>Gingerbread Cookie</strong> decorating kit comes with <strong>everything you need</strong> for sweet holiday fun. Little ones will have loads of fun designing their own gingerbread people and snowmen with supplies that include icing, sprinkles, candies and jawbreakers.</p>
<p><strong>We’ve got great tips for creating a classic gingerbread house</strong>. Grab a mug of cocoa or cider and get decorating.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Get ready:</strong> Set out all of your materials before you begin. Separate candy into small dishes—muffin tins are a great way to keep everything organized! The kits come with plenty of decorations, but for more options, dip into your pantry and explore your creativity. Try our <em>Compliments</em> Wheat Squares cereal for shingles.</li>
<li><strong>Catch drips:</strong> Lay strips of parchment under the edges of your house before you begin. Pull gently to remove them once the gingerbread house is decorated and dry.</li>
<li><strong>Lay the Foundation:</strong> Resist the urge to glob on icing when joining the edges. The joins will take longer to dry and be less stable. <strong>Pro tip:</strong> Wrap string around the house base—it will hold the walls together when you attach the roof.</li>
<li><strong>Make sure it’s sturdy:</strong> Before decorating, make sure the icing holding your gingerbread house together is completely dry. <strong>Leave it at least an hour.</strong> While you’re waiting for the icing to dry, decorate cookie figures like snowmen or gingerbread people.</li>
<li><strong>Decorate with care:</strong> Once the house is built, put little ones in charge of simple tasks, such as choosing and adding sprinkles and candies to the house.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Product availability may vary by store. <a title="Find your Sobeys store" href="http://www.sobeys.com/en/Find-A-Store.aspx" target="_blank">Check your local Sobeys</a></em><em> for details.</em></p>
